us","Straight sinus","Transverse sinus","Inferior sagittal sinus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperficial middle cerebral vein drains into the cavernous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E. It courses along the lateral sulcus (Sylvian fissure) and collects blood from the lateral surface of the cerebral hemisphere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into the superior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The superior cerebral veins drain into this sinus, not the superficial middle cerebral vein\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into the straight sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The straight sinus primarily receives the great cerebral vein (of Galen) and inferior sagittal sinus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into the transverse sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - While some inferior cerebral veins drain here, the superficial middle cerebral vein does not\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrains into the inferior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - This sinus receives drainage from the medial surface of the cerebral hemispheres\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the venous drainage patterns of the brain is important as these pathways can be affected by various pathological processes including thrombosis and vascular malformations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The superficial middle cerebral vein drains the lateral surface of the cerebral hemisphere into the cavernous sinus.","The superior cerebral veins drain the superolateral cerebral surface into the superior sagittal sinus.","The inferior cerebral veins drain the inferior cerebral surface into the transverse sinus and cavernous sinus."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.